  abstract = {Fire frequency in low-elevation coniferous forests in western North America has greatly 12 declined since the late 1800s. In many areas, this has increased tree density and the proportion of 13 shade-tolerant species, reduced resource availability, and increased forest susceptibility to forest 14 insect pests and high-severity wildfire. In response, treatments are often implemented with the 15 goal of increasing ecosystem resilience by increasing resistance to disturbance. We capitalized 16 on an existing replicated study of fire and stand density treatments in a ponderosa pine (Pinus 17 18 ponderosa)-Douglas-fir (Pseudotsuga menziesii) forest in western Montana, U.S. that experienced a naturally occurring mountain pine beetle (MPB; Dendroctonus ponderosae) 19 outbreak five years after implementation of fuels treatments. We explored whether treatment 20 effects on tree-level defense and stand structure affected resistance to MPB. Mortality from MPB 21 was highest in the denser, untreated control and burn-only treatments, with approximately 50\% 22 and 39\%, respectively, of ponderosa pine killed during the outbreak, compared to almost no 23 mortality in the thin-only and thin-burn treatments. Thinning treatments, with or without fire, 24 dramatically increased tree growth and resin ducts relative to control and burn-only treatments. 25 Prescribed burning did not increase resin ducts, but did cause changes in resin chemistry that 26 may have affected MPB communication and lowered attack success. While ponderosa pine 27 remained dominant in the thin and thin-burn treatments after the outbreak, the high pine 28 mortality in the control and burn-only treatment caused a shift in species dominance to Douglas- 29 fir. The high Douglas-fir component in the control and burn-only treatments due to 20th century 30 31 32 fire exclusion, coupled with high pine mortality from MPB, has likely reduced resilience of this forest beyond the ability to return to a ponderosa pine-dominated system in the absence of further fire or mechanical treatment. Our results show treatments designed to increase resistance 33 to high-severity fire in ponderosa pine-dominated forests in the Northern Rockies can also 34 increase resistance to MPB, even during an outbreak. This study suggests that fuel and 35 restoration treatments in fire-dependent ponderosa pine forests that reduce tree density increase 36 ecosystem resilience in the short term, while the reintroduction of fire is important for long-term 37 resilience.},
