e reduced to a single treatment (cutting and\textbackslash{}nburning) in future experiments to investigate the impacts of patch\textbackslash{}nharvesting on community dynamics. Simpler factorial experiments can be\textbackslash{}ndesigned than if cutting and burning had to be considered as separate\textbackslash{}ntreatments.\textbackslash{}n5. There was no difference in the establishment of tall grass species or\textbackslash{}nwoody species between managed and unmanaged plots.\textbackslash{}n6. Results suggest that patches of grassland could be left unmanaged on\textbackslash{}na 2-year rotation without significantly altering the composition of the\textbackslash{}nplant community, thereby providing refugia for cover-dependent faunal\textbackslash{}nspecies.},
