  volume = {20},
  issn = {13528505},
  abstract = {All ecological communities experience change over time. One method to\textbackslash{}nquantify temporal variation in the patterns of relative abundance of\textbackslash{}ncommunities is time lag analysis (TLA). It uses a distance-based\textbackslash{}napproach to study temporal community dynamics by regressing community\textbackslash{}ndissimilarity over increasing time lags (one-unit lags, two-unit lags,\textbackslash{}nthree-unit lags). Here, we suggest some modifications to the method and\textbackslash{}nrevaluate its potential for detecting patterns of community change. We\textbackslash{}napply Hellinger distance based TLA to artificial data simulating\textbackslash{}ncommunities with different levels of directional and stochastic dynamics\textbackslash{}nand analyse their effects on the slope and its statistical significance.\textbackslash{}nWe conclude that statistical significance of the TLA slope (obtained by\textbackslash{}na Monte Carlo permutation procedure) is a valid criterion to\textbackslash{}ndiscriminate between (i) communities with directional change in species\textbackslash{}ncomposition, regardless whether it is caused by directional abundance\textbackslash{}nchange of the species or by stochastic change according to a Markov\textbackslash{}nprocess, and (ii) communities that are composed of species with\textbackslash{}npopulation sizes oscillating around a constant mean or communities whose\textbackslash{}nspecies abundances are governed by a white noise process. TLA slopes\textbackslash{}nrange between 0.02 and 0.25, depending on the proportions of species\textbackslash{}nwith different dynamics; higher proportions of species with constant\textbackslash{}nmeans imply shallower slopes; and higher proportions of species with\textbackslash{}nstochastic dynamics or directional change imply steeper slopes. These\textbackslash{}nvalues are broadly in line with TLA slopes from real world data. Caution\textbackslash{}nmust be exercised when TLA is used for the comparison of community time\textbackslash{}nseries with different lengths since the slope depends on time series\textbackslash{}nlength and tends to decrease non-linearly with it.},
